May 18, 2017
Jake

        rated it
        it was ok



For context, I read this book out loud to several fifth-grade classes over the course of a year, so (unfortunately) I know it pretty intimately. I discussed the book with each class throughout the readings, and most classes picked up on the same issues with the book that I'm about to list now. Zach's Lie is a weak fulfillment of a plot with potential, a plot that could have been engaging and dynamic but fails in large part due to flimsy writing. The book is basically a puppet show where every ch
For context, I read this book out loud to several fifth-grade classes over the course of a year, so (unfortunately) I know it pretty intimately. I discussed the book with each class throughout the readings, and most classes picked up on the same issues with the book that I'm about to list now. Zach's Lie is a weak fulfillment of a plot with potential, a plot that could have been engaging and dynamic but fails in large part due to flimsy writing. The book is basically a puppet show where every character is made out of cardboard and moves erratically and nonsensically to the whims of Roland Smith. With the help of an editor and some time spent thinking about the feasibility of his plot, this story could have been told well, but it wasn't. For starters, nearly every main character in this book is stupid and does stupid things, often just to keep the shambling plot moving forward. Jack keeps a journal throughout the whole book of his daily life, including details about their journey through the witness protection program and the events that led up to it. Hmm, I wonder what could happen as a result of this. No clue! /s(view spoiler)[And Patricia somehow thinks it's a great idea to send an old postcard from their new location (didn't even think to drive to Salt Lake City, already mentioned in the book, or literally anywhere else to send it) to their old lawyer, drawing a connection between their new lives and the Osbornes. Also, they don't discuss a backup plan, nor do they utilize their biggest and most well-trained resource, the witness protection agents. And somehow, Alonzo is so omniscient that he can have someone constantly checking the mail of the Osborne's lawyer, "just in case." Sure, OK. This whole scenario feels like Smith had no clue how to drag the drug cartel back into their lives and he wanted to, so he dreamed up this sequence and hoped nobody would actually think about it. And Jack, upon reading his dad's journal with a note that says "don't read this, it's dangerous," takes the journal with him to school. Sure, OK, he's protecting it by keeping it with him -- I can buy that, makes sense. He then immediately blows my mind and opens it as soon as he gets to school and the pages spill out of the dangerous journal so that Peter can steal the one about Alonzo and put himself into "grave" danger. Literally every fifth grader could not fathom why he would do this. Wanna know why Jack opened it? Because Smith needed him to do so to add drama to the story. It's a crutch that he relies on, again and again, and the story suffers for it.  (hide spoiler)]The plot shouldn't develop the actions of the characters; that's why so many of these characters in Zach's Lie feel like cardboard cutouts that only move and speak when asked to. Nobody is more than what they're presented as in the first paragraph of their introduction, with the exception of Sam, the only character with any hint of depth. Alonzo is the big bad that wears all black and runs a drug cartel. Catalin is the pretty, nice girl. Darrell has red hair and likes hunting and video games. Most other characters have so little to them, I can't even remember how to even try to describe them. Various conversations exist only to infodump and are entirely devoid of personality. One passage, around the middle of the book, had Cat telling Jack the backstory of Peter's parents for no conceivable reason except to tell readers about his dad (and ultimately, that information also had no relevance to anything, really). It also happens very obviously in other sections of the story, like when Jack visited the Elko museum early on to find out everything about the Basques. History lesson and "backstory" shoehorned into the book via an addiction to museums that is not mentioned a single time afterwards. Nitpicking now, but multiple times throughout the book, lengthy back-and-forth conversations occur… and Smith does not use dialogue tags. It goes like this:"Hello," says A. "Hi," says B. "It's a nice day out today.""Yes, it is.""I'm glad we went on a walk today.""Did C like the present I got her?" "Yeah, it was really nice. She wanted me to tell you thank you."Who got C the present? Did you have to go back and re-track who said what?It was especially bad because nobody had any semblance of voice, as you'd expect from cardboard characters. I had to back up and tell classes who said which line more than once, which was more than one too many. The occasional bright spots in his ideas (Commander IF as a whole was one that stood out to me, as did the idea of (view spoiler)[Catalin liking Jack's fake blue eyes (hide spoiler)]) were cloaked in the complete lack of character development and nonsensical plot. A solid plot idea and an action-y conclusion doth not a good book make.I would not waste the time of future students by reading Zach's Lie to them.
...more






